entry.title: Make window-open-blank-from-different-initiator.html use slow.py instead
entry.content:
The test initially used infinite-slow-response.py to make a navigation

that never commits. However, infinite-slow-response.py will actually

commit as the HTTP response for the navigation *started* (it just never

finished), unblocking the navigation from committing. To achieve the

goal of having a navigation that practically never commits, we will

use slow.py, which will not start the HTTP response until after a very

long delay, making a navigation that's pending for a very long time.

entry.title: Add MultiScreenCaptureAllowedForUrls to control getAllScreensMedia
entry.content:
Before this change, the getAllScreensMedia could only be enabled

through the soon to be deprecated

GetDisplayMediaSetSelectAllScreensAllowedForUrls policy. This change

is a step towards the pivot from arbitrary origins to IWA origins

entry.title: media/gpu/vaapi: Prepare image processor for NativePixmap
entry.content:
This is done in a few parts. First is to migrate from

VaapiWrapper::CreateVASurfaceForPixmap() to

CreateVASurfaceForFrameResource(). This gives a few things:

1. It unblocks use of frames with storage type of STORAGE_DMABUFS.

2. It reduce file descriptor duplication for NativePixmapFrameResource

frames.

3. It reduces the amount of code.



This also removes restrictions that only permit VideoFrame::StorageType

of STORAGE_GPU_MEMORY_BUFFER. NativePixmapFrameResource uses

STORAGE_DMABUFS. Use of gfx::GpuMemoryBufferId has been replaced with

gfx::GenericSharedMemoryID, which can be provided by frames backed by

GPUMemoryBuffer or NativePixmap via FrameResource::GetSharedMemoryId().



Additionally, there are some cosmetic changes: renaming

GetSurfaceForVideoFrame() since VideoFrame is not used anymore, and

switching its frame parameter from scoped_refptr to

const FrameResource& since ownership of the frame does not need to be

transferred.

if the field indicates that initial sync is not done.

entry.title: [ios] Delete SyncSetupService
entry.content:
If there are any behavior changes, they should only happen in code

paths where kReplaceSyncPromosWithSignInPromos is disabled, and

that code should be deleted soon anyway (the feature is launched).



There were 2 kinds of methods left in this service.

1) Wrappers around SyncSetupInProgressHandle: CommitSyncChanges(),

HasUncommittedChanges(), PrepareForFirstSyncSetup().

2) A wrapper around

SyncUserSettings::SetInitialSyncFeatureSetupComplete().



Calls to (1) can be further divided in 2 kinds:

a) Holding a SyncSetupInProgressHandle before doing

SetSyncFeatureRequested() & SetInitialSyncFeatureSetupComplete() [1]

-> Calls deleted in this CL. This might cause the sync engine to

start a bit earlier but is believed to be harmless.

b) Holding a SyncSetupInProgressHandle while showing the data type

toggles to syncing users -> Replaced with direct use of

SyncSetupInProgressHandle.



Calls to (2) are replaced with direct use of SyncUserSettings. The

original wrapper had some extra guarding by CanSyncFeatureStart() [2].

I think that predicate is guaranteed to be true in all current callers

so I just removed the check. But as mentioned before, even if that's

not true, these code paths will be deleted soon anyway.



[1] Note: GrantSyncConsent() calls PrepareForFirstSyncSetup(), which

holds a SyncSetupInProgressHandle. CommitSyncChanges() releases the

handle.

entry.title: Migrate PlusAddressSyncBridge to in-memory changelist + sql::Transaction
entry.content:
PlusAddressTable implements SyncMetadataStore and is used to store

metadata for PLUS_ADDRESS. Currently, this is done by implementing

PlusAddressSyncBridge::CreateMetadataChangeList() via PlusAddressTable.



In the sync bridge's ApplyIncrementalSyncChanges() and

ApplyDisableSyncChanges(), the metadata changes are then ignored, since

they were already written to the table via the metadata change list.

Apply(Incremental|Disable)SyncChanges() simply applies the model data

changes.



As a WebDatabaseTable, changes to PlusAddressTable are only persisted on

disk when the ongoing transaction is committed (there is always one

active top-level transaction, but nested transactions are supported as

well). By only committing at the end of

Apply(Incremental|Disable)SyncChanges(), it is ensured that metadata and

model data are committed in a single transaction.



Problems can arise when some of the operations on PlusAddressTable fail,

though. In this case, the operation in the sync bridge would early

return, without ever committing. But since the code relies on the

top-level WebDatabase transaction, other code (in particular, the

WebDatabase itself on shutdown) will commit these changes eventually.

This leaves metadata and model data out of sync.



This changes fixes this problem, by:

- Implementing CreateMetadataChangeList() with an

InMemoryMetadataChangeList.

- In Apply(Incremental|Disable)SyncChanges(), opening a nested

sql::Transaction, instead of reyling on the top-level one.

- Transferring the metadata changes from the in-memory metadata change

list to PlusAddressTable in Apply(Incremental|Disable)SyncChanges(),

inside the same nested sql::Transaction.



If any operation fails, the nested sql::Transaction is never committed,

and thus it is ensured that model and metadata are always consistent.

entry.title: Adjust the end of the next paragraph in FormatSelection()
entry.content:
This CL adjusts the end of the next paragraph in FormatSelection()

if `end_of_paragraph_to_move` is updated with `selected_list_item`

in TryIndentingAsListItem() while list items are indented.

Normally, FormatSelection() runs FormatRange() for each paragraph

can be updated with the last child of `selected_list_item`. In

that case, the updated end position of the paragraph to move

should be notified of FormatSelection() to start the next round

from the correct position.

entry.content:
This CL simplifies the logic of OzoneImageGLTexturesHolder's calculation

case, using external sampling is equivalent to "the buffer format passed

the single-planar format of the plane be passed in.



As this is the platform-specific and service-side equivalent of the

logic that we are rolling out with ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget(),

we put this change under the same killswitch.

entry.title: Don't bind a null LayoutText pointer to a reference
entry.content:
https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5308656

introduced a null reference, which is undefined behavior and flagged by

UBSan. If text_layout_object was null, it is UB to write

*text_layout_object. Although the parameter was ignored

(ShouldUpdateLayoutByReattaching will return true and thus

UpdateTextLayoutObject will ignore layout_text), even binding the

reference is too late.



We could fix this by making LayoutText a pointer, but then that method's

API contract is weird because layout_text would need to be non-null when

by_reattach is true. Instead, since this helper method is so short and

only called twice, I've simply inlined it into the two call sites.

entry.title: Invalidate weak pointers in search request before stopping search
entry.content:
Before this CL, only `HandleSearchSourceResults` was guaranteed to be a

no-op after stopping the search - however, the individual

`Handle*SearchResults` methods (one for each search source) were still

called. Any logic inside of those methods - including emitting metrics

and post-processing of results - are still run before calling the

now-no-op `HandleSearchSourceResults`. The only way we guarantee that

`Handle*SearchResults` methods are no-ops is by resetting metrics, so

they do not get emitted in these methods.



Invalidate all weak pointers - and therefore bound callbacks to

`Handle*SearchResults` methods - to ensure that `Handle*SearchResults`

methods are never called in the first place. This prevents the (no-op)

code for emitting metrics, and preprocessing search results (to pass to

a no-op method) from running in the first place.

entry.title: Move search request code from controller to separate class
entry.content:
This separates the responsibilities of aggregation (burn-in) and

ordering - still in the search controller - and performing the requests

to the search sources themselves - now in a new search request class.



This CL is a pure move - the search request class currently has the same

lifetime as the search controller. Future CLs may change the lifetime of

the search request class so it lives for as long as a search itself -

constructed on search start, destructed on search stop.



We will not add tests for the search request class until it is

refactored more. As it is used directly from the search controller, and

we have extensive test coverage on that, most search request class

behaviours are (indirectly) tested from those tests.

entry.title: media/video/VEA: Add DropFrameMetadata to BitstreamBufferMetadata
entry.content:
BitstreamBufferMetadta for a dropped frame doesn't have any info about

codec metadata (e.g. spatial index). This is because no valid value

can be filled to some of the codec metadata (e.g. temporal index) and

we would like to avoid a client from wrongly referencing invalid

values.

However, this makes a client difficult to handle a dropped frame in

SVC encoding because a client cannot know a spatial layer index.



This CL introduces DropFrameMetadata. It is set if and only if a

frame is dropped. The metadata has useful info for the dropped frame.

It has spatial index so far.
